\par }{\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 Lodovik would never underestimate the wiles and intelligence of a thinking machine that had survived twenty thousand years. But an hour passed, then two hours, and 
he realized he had entered a precarious state of decision lock. No course of action seemed to lead to success.}{\f1\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 
\par }{\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 He jerked free of the lock and powered up all his conserved systems. The flood of energy and strength\emdash the sensation of his skin repairing itself, leaving no discernible scars\emdash 
 was refreshing. He had at least one major advantage over humans. He did not care in the least whether he lived or died, only that he could serve humans in the way that shone forth so clearly now.}{\f1\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 
\par }{\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 neel had mentioned the opposing robots\emdash the Calvini-ans. He had heard about them on a few occasions, centuries ago, from other robots\emdash 
the robotic equivalent of nasty rumors. If they still existed (Daneel had not made it clear whether they did or not) then they might have established so
me small presence on Trantor. This would only be done if they felt they had some chance of defeating Daneel.}{\f1\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 
\par }{\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 Lodovik dressed quickly and adjusted his appearance once more to the limit of what he could accomplish just through volition. He now seemed much yo
unger, a little thinner, and his hair changed color to a shining yellow.}{\f1\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 
\par }{\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 He now resembled neither the old Lodovik nor the new Rissik Numant. Nevertheless, his basic body plan and physiognomy were the same; and, of course, his brain was the same. He would n
ot fool Daneel for long, should they meet.}{\f1\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 
\par }{\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 Lodovik knew he would have to leave this apartment and begin his search immediately. He doubted he would have more than a day before Daneel would suspect something was amiss.}{\f1\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 

\par }{\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 He would have to educate himself and do all he could within that very short period of time.}{\f1\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 
\par }{\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 Fortunately, Lodovik knew where to begin\emdash in the private library willed to the Emperor Agis XIV by one of the richest proprietors of the Fleshplay, the eccentric sch
olar Huy Markin. The Emperor had passed it on to the Imperial University of Pan-Galactic Culture without bothering to examine or even transfer the material\emdash 
a specialized and almost useless collection, so it was said. The Imperial University had given it over to the charge of the Imperial Library, then both had ignored it as well.}{\f1\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 
\par }{\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 As honorary Provost of the Imperial University, a rank conferred by Linge Chen some years ago, Lodovik had been given the code keys to all of the University's grounds and facilities\emdash 
including the library of Huy Markin.}{\f1\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 
\par }{\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 There, he would find thousands of years of legends and myths, gathered from around the Galaxy; the distilled}{\f1\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 
\par }{\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 dreams, visions, and nightmares of tens of millions of human worlds.}{\f1\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 
\par }{\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 He could think of no better place to begin.}{\f1\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 
\par }{\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 An undercurrent of tension flowed along the tiers of slide-ways of the Agora of Vendors, as if the people smelled some impossible storm coming.}{\f1\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 
\par }{\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 Klia looked up as they walked beside a large courtyard rising through the agora. Her eyes followed a curvin
g support at one side of the courtyard, past hundreds of levels, all the way to the distant ceil, perhaps three or four kilometers above, where the support seemed to blend into perfect golden-clouded sky. Then she looked down through dozens of more tiers,
 
all crowded, the hum of hundreds of thousands of voices echoing up and down them until it became a low, constant roar. Had she ever heard a real ocean, she might have compared the sound to the roll of the waves and tides; but all she could compare it to w
as the endless bellow of the two rivers, One and Two, somehow channeled and subdued, but no less powerful.}{\f1\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 
\par }{\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 Her nose wrinkled, and she followed Brann closely. The transport, tricked out with decorative wheel covers and a gaily colored tarp folded over its last remaining crate, rolled silently behind them.}{
\f1\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 
\par }{\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 They could never catch more than glimpses of the uppermost tiers through the courtyard air passages. The worlds of the baronial families were invisible from this far down in the hierarchy. One or two levels 
at the bottom of the agora were reserved for the citizens.}{\f1\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 
\par }{\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 Along the lower and middle tiers, the multitudinous social ranks of Tranter's essential Greys moved in their characteristic subdued clothes, men and women dressed very}{\f1\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 
\par }{\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 41.}{\f1\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 
\par }{\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 much alike, only the numerous children allowed touches of bright color.}{\f1\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 
\par }{\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 The Greys strolling the agora, off watch for the hour or perhaps on yearly two-day vacations, parted for Brann, Klia, and the floating transport, casting looks of dull curiosity at the
 crates, perhaps wondering if they carried something they could afford to buy, anything, to relieve the boredom...}{\f1\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 
\par }{\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 Klia understood the Greys' functions well enough\emdash tenders of Trantor's vast hierarchies of submission and response, allocators of resources an
d funding, administrators of data inflow, civic and planetary works. Her people had seldom dealt with Greys directly, for they had been overseen by the Municipal Progress Bureau of Dahl, whose ranks were filled with Dahlites handpicked each generation by 
the Greys of the Regional Works and Energy Council. Naturally, she felt contempt for all such, and had no doubt they would have felt contempt for her, had they even known of her existence.}{\f1\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 
\par }{\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 But now she saw the Greys themselves watched and made uneasy. Police
 officers strolled this level in groups of three or four, not the officers of the district, but Imperial Specials, the same that had stalked Klia and forced her to seek out Kallusin, the man in dusty green. Families of Greys engaged in browsing the stalls
 
of the vendors drew their children in close and observed the Specials with suspicious eyes, eyes characterized by a flat kind of bureaucratic intelligence. They knew law and social structure, it was in their blood, and they knew something was amiss here, 
forces out of balance. They withdrew from the arcades and lanes as fast as they could, and this level was quickly emptying of customers.}{\f1\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 
\par }{\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 Brann grimly walked on.}{\f1\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 
\par }{\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 "We should get out of here. They're probably hunting us, " Klia said in a whisper, hanging on his shoulder briefly to bring her mouth closer to his ear.}{\f1\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 
\par }{\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 He shook his head. "Don't think so, " he said. "We have to deliver this order. "}{\f1\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 
\par }{\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 "What if they catch us?" Klia asked, her face wrinkled with worry.}{\f1\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 
\par }{\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 "Stay calm. They won't, " Brann said. "I know a dozen secret passages out of here, a dozen shopkeepers right here"\emdash he swung his hand loosely from the hip at the stalls and shops to their left and right\emdash 
"who won't mind our passing through. "}{\f1\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 
\par }{\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 Klia drew up her shoulders, not at all reassured. She had been thi
nking of ways to shake free of Plussix's control, but not into the arms of the police. And, in point of fact, in the last hour or so, as they had made their deliveries of Anacreon folk-dolls and other baubles, she had given less and less thought to escapi
ng at all...}{\f1\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 
\par }{\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 
Brann provided such a masculine contrast to the ethereal, dry, and passionless Greys that he shone like a beacon in Klia's eyes. She had been thinking, in that instinctive and youthful region below rational assessment, of being strongly tied to
 this large, powerful male, with his sympathetic black eyes and immense, agile hands. She had thought of the implied benefits of these ties\emdash of privacy and intimacy\emdash and she had wondered what she could do, in private, to impress him.}{
\f1\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 
\par }{\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 She felt sure he was thinking many of the same thoughts, and, for once, she believed him when he said he was trying none of his mentalic abilities on her.}{\f1\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 
\par }{\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 The untidy collision of apprehension and passionate speculation gave her a headache. "Let's hurry, " she said.}{\f1\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 
\par }{\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 Brann shook his head stubbornly. "They're not after us, " he said.}{\f1\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 
\par }{\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 "How can you be so damned sure?" she whispered harshly.}{\f1\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 
\par }{\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 "Listen\emdash " He pointed into the crowds north of them, thickening and roiling where police were congregating. Klia listened with both her ears and her mind\emdash 
and felt the unwanted, familiar trace of the woman who had hunted her before. She felt the woman's awareness feather the}{\f1\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 
\par }{\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 edges of her mind, and she reached out to grip Brann's arm.}{\f1\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 
\par }{\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 
"It's her!" she whispered. The crowds were moving this way. He drew close and nodded, put his arm around her as if to protect her. Without hesitation, Klia accepted his protection. Suddenly, from the middle of the surging Greys less than a dozen meters aw
ay, a small motor cart pushed through, floating a few centimeters above the causeway. On the cart sat a young, blond, clean-faced Imperial security officer, two armed guards, and a small, intense woman with dark frizzy red hair.}{
\f1\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 
\par }{\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 Klia felt the woman scanning the Greys to either side, saw her wizened, unattractive face turning back and forth as the cart floated slowly and deliberately through. There was no way out\emdash 
no exit. Blank walls of closed shops flanked them.}{\f1\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 
\par }{\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 They were within three meters, with only four 
or five Greys in between, when Vara Liso suddenly swiveled on her seat and stared directly at Klia. Their eyes locked. Klia felt the touch in her mind very strongly, rebuffed it, almost literally pushed the intruder out of her mind\emdash 
and made Vara Liso jerk on the cart as if stung.}{\f1\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 
\par }{\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 
Liso continued to glare at her, then her face was wreathed with a sudden, beatific smile. She nodded briefly at Klia, as if acknowledging an equal, and looked away. The touch dropped to a mere feather again, passed without focusing, went elsewhere.}{
\f1\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 
\par }{\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 Brann pulled her gently to one side of the aisle. "She was the one who hunted you\emdash wasn't she?" he asked.}{\f1\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 
\par }{\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 Klia nodded. "But\emdash she ignored me!" Klia said, looking up at Brann in astonishment. "She found me\emdash she could have had me\emdash " \'bb}{\f1\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 
\par }{\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 "Us, " Brann interjected.}{\f1\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 
\par }{\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 "And she ignored us!"}{\f1\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 
\par }{\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 Brann frowned deeply and shook his head. "Kallusin and}{\f1\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 
\par }{\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 Plussix will want to know about this, " he said. "Who is she after now?"}{\f1\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 
\par }{\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 "Are we going back?" Klia asked.}{\f1\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 
\par }{\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 "We have two more deliveries, " Brann said, and grinned d
own at her with an expression not of stolidity or stubbornness, but of a massive kind of impishness. "Trantor has survived twelve thousand years. This news can wait a couple of hours. "}{\f1\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 
\par }{\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 42.}{\f1\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 
\par }{\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 Lodovik approached the small, thick door in its darkened vestibule
. A light flashed on as he touched the door, and a small voice asked for the appropriate code for entry. He spoke the code precisely, and the door opened to let him in.}{\f1\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 
\par }{\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 Within, the library was cast in penumbrous spots of soft golden light. The first room w
as circular, less than three meters across, with an empty table in the middle. On the table was set a small, angled riser, like a lectern, but obviously meant to hold ancient information devices such as paper books. The table and riser were many thousands
 of years old, surrounded and protected by a surface-hugging conservation field, not unlike a personal shield.}{\f1\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 
\par }{\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 Lodovik stood before the table and waited for several seconds. A melodious female voice, that of Huy Markin herself, now used by the collection's automated server, then asked for a subject or subjects to search for.}
{\f1\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 
\par }{\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 "Calvin, Susan, " he said, and felt a small shiver within at that ancient and powerful name. He did not expect this blunt approach to work, and it did not. The server listed thirty-two e
ntries on various Calvins, two Susans\emdash all mere thousands of years old, and having nothing to do with the mother of robots. There was no record of Calvinians.}{\f1\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 
\par }{\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 "Eternals, " he suggested, "with reference to conspiracies of immortal beings. " A few seconds lat
er, the server projected a text manuscript onto the top of the table and the riser, giving the remarkable impression of a real and open book.}{\f1\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 
\par }{\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 "*Myths of the Eternals, '" the server said. "By a committee of three hundred authors, in ninety-two volumes of te
xt with twenty-nine hours of other documentary media, compiled G. E. 8045-8068. This is the authoritative work on a subject little studied nowadays, and this is the only known copy on Trantor, or indeed on the prime thousand worlds of the Empire. "}{
\f1\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 
\par }{\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 Lodovik watched a chair rise from the floor, but as he did not need the chair, he told it to retract. He stood before the book and began to absorb the material at high speed.}{\f1\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 

\par }{\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 There was a lot of information that seemed completely useless, probably untrue, legends 
and fabulous stories compiled over thousands of years. He noted with some interest that in the past few millennia, such legends and even this kind of storytelling seemed to have diminished considerably, and not just on the topics of the Eternals: humans o
n Trantor and most of the prime worlds had simply lost interest in fabulous tales of any kind, or even in the more spectacular episodes of history.}{\f1\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 
\par }{\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 Humanity's childhood had long since passed. Now, the concerns of the Imperial cultures were strictly practical.}{\f1\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 
\par }{\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 
Humor had declined as well; this, he found suggested in an afterword to this set, appended by a scholar less than fifteen hundred years before. Then, suddenly, the recorded image of Huy Markin herself appeared in the small chamber, frozen, with a captio
n glowing faintly at her feet: Excerpt from spoken lecture. There was no date given.}{\f1\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 
\par }{\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 "Retrieve and play, " Lodovik instructed.}{\f1\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 
\par }{\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 The image moved and spoke. "The decline of humor and comedy in the myths and entertainments of the modern Imperial culture seems inevitable to the sober gentry and Greys of}{\f1\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 

\par }{\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 our time. But certain meritocrats feel a peculiar lack in the present panoply of the fantastic arts. All has been subsumed by the immediate and the practical; modern humans of the ruling and imaginative classes d
ream less and laugh less than ever before in history. This does not hold for the citizens, but their humor, for thousands of years, has remained a raucous collection of generic jokes and tales at the expense of other classes, showing little insight and ev
en less effectiveness as satire. All has been subsumed by the quest for stability and comfort... "}{\f1\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 
\par }{\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 Lodovik pushed ahead through this rather long lecture until he found the link with the text he was searching, and his subject. "Some, " Huy Markin said, "have
 laid blame for these intellectual failures on the perfidious influence of brain fever, contracted by nearly all children at an early age, but somehow never more than lightly affecting the sturdy foundations of the citizens. The gentry and meritocrats, ho
w
ever, according to some statisticians, have apparently suffered substantial losses in intellectual capacity. Legends about the misty origins of brain fever abound. The most prominent myth is of an ancient war between the worlds Earth and Solaria. Robots, 
it is said, carried this disease from world to world. Some of these robots... "}{\f1\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 
\par }{\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 Lodovik marveled that this analysis had been judged the product of an eccentric by the University's finest scholars. Not even Hari Seldon had seen fit to look into the collection\emdash 
perhaps because of some interdiction by Daneel.}{\f1\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 
\par }{\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 
He sped ahead. "... The most common explanation of brain fever in all these myths is that of human competition for the colonization of the Galaxy. Brain fever may have been a weapon in such a competition. But a persistent alternative explanation points to
 
the Eternals, who fought with the servants of Solaria to prevent a hideous crime, the details of which have since been totally expunged from all known records. The Eternals, it has been said, created brain fever to control the destructive urges of a human
 race out of control.}{\f1\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 
\par }{\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 The Eternals have been described as immortal humans, but have also been described as long-lived robots of extraordinary intelligence... "}{\f1\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 
\par }{\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 There it was again, Lodovik thought. The attempt by robots to control the destructive tendencies of humans\emdash but what was this great crime?}{\f1\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 
\par }{\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 Was it the same crime hinted at by Daneel, supposedly carried out by those robots who, very early on, disagreed with Daneel's plans?}{\f1\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 
\par }{\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 Daneel was quite obviously an Eternal, perhaps the Eternal, the oldest thinking machine in the Galaxy...}{\f1\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 
\par }{\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 The oldest and most dedicated puppet master.}{\f1\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 
\par }{\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 Lodovik looked up from the projection he was reading and tried to find the source of this interjection. The words disturbed him; they did not seem to originate in any of the branches of his mentality.}{
\f1\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 
\par }{\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 
He remembered the faint touches he had felt on the dying ship, the impressions of a ghostly intelligence interested in his plight. Until now, he had dismissed this as an effect of neutrino damage in his mind; but Yan Kansarv had found no detec
table damage.}{\f1\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 
\par }{\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 The memory could be replayed quite easily, and analyzed. The label Volarr or Voldarr was attached to these faint traces, these subliminal touches.}{\f1\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 
\par }{\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 But nothing useful could be drawn from these memories.}{\f1\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 
\par }{\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 Lodovik resumed his main search, and sca
nned the main volumes in less than three hours. He could have searched and absorbed the material much more rapidly, but the library displays had been set for human researchers, not robots.}{\f1\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 
\par }{\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 Robots of human or superior intelligence, every volume and bit of documentation in Markin's library suggested, had long since ceased to function, if they had ever existed at all.}{
\f1\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 
\par }{\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 Lodovik shut down the projectors and left the library. As he passed through the impressive doorway, the image of Huy Markin appeared.}{\f1\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 
\par }{\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 "You're the first visitor in two decades, " the image told him. "Please come again!"}{\f1\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 
\par }{\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 Lodovik stared at the image as it faded. He stepped out from under the overhang that shielded the doorway and strolled along a mid-class tier of the Agora of Vendors, among the Greys. So many pieces to fit together
\emdash in a puzzle thousands of years old, with so many pieces missing or deliberately obscured.}{\f1\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 
\par }{\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 What echoed through Lodovik's positronic brain, cascading into conclusions that reinforced impressions and hypotheses already made, 
was the effect of Imperial culture (and brain fever?) on human nature. Where once the human race had laughed and reveled in the absurd, in the products of pure imagination, they now earnestly pursued stasis. The leading artists, scientists, engineers, phi
losophers, and politicians, were eager to confirm the discoveries of the past, not make new ones. And now, few even remembered the past well enough to know what had already been discovered! The past itself was no longer of interest\emdash 
had not been for centuries, even thousands of years.}{\f1\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 
\par }{\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 The light had gone out. Stability and stasis across millennia had led to stagnation.}{\f1\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 
\par }{\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 Daneel uses his psychohistorian to confirm what he must already know\emdash that the forest is overgrown, filled with rotten wood, desperately in need of a conflagration that he will not allow to happen!}{
\f1\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 
\par }{\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 Lodovik paused at a surge of the crowd through the agora, listened to murmurs and shouts. A retinue of Imperial Specials was pushing through the crowd. Lodovik backed away, found an alley of smaller sho
ps. He wanted to avoid making himself conspicuous in any way. He could not know who might be watching\emdash and who might be reporting back to Daneel, human or robot. While he was not yet behaving suspiciously\emdash }{
\f1\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 
\par }{\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 Just outside the alley, he heard a woman's shrill shouts, commands. "Don't let it get away!"}{\f1\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 
\par }{\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 He paused, turned, and saw two of the Specials turn into the alley, followed by a woman riding a small cart. He felt something brush through him, like a feather, and deduced instantly that the woman was a mentalic.}{
\f1\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 
\par }{\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 He knew a little of the mentalics assembled by Hari Sel-don to provide a backup and alternative to his First Foundation, but none of them were as strong as this woman\emdash 
and none of them would have dreamed of pursuing him!}{\f1\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 
\par }{\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 Quite clearly, that was what the woman was doing. She pointed and screeched again. Lodovik knew it would make no difference if he altered his appearance\emdash this woman was fixed on something below the surface.}{
\f1\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 
\par }{\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 She recognizes your difference.}{\f1\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 
\par }{\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 Again the voice, the interior presence\emdash producing a cascading conclusion he might not have reached by himself: the woman was feathering the fields associated with his indium sponge brain!}{
\f1\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 
\par }{\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 When pressed, Lodovik could move very rapidly indeed. One moment, the shoppers in the narrow alley of antiques dealers and
 sellers of trinkets became aware that the Specials were approaching a plump and homely looking man\emdash and the next, he was gone.}{\f1\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 
\par }{\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 Vara Liso stood on her cart, her face flaming with anger and excitement. "He's escaped!" she shouted, and she struck at the young police escort with her hand, as if he were a wayward child. "You let him escape!"}{
\f1\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 
\par }{\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 Then, from another alley, more Specials appeared.}{\f1\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 
\par }{\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 T
he plump man walked quickly ahead of them, herded by the press of a crowd of shoppers, like unwanted fish pulled together in a dragnet. The Greys expressed their anger with shouts and threats of complaining to their class senate.}{
\f1\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 
\par }{\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 Lodovik dared not move too quickly among so many people. He might injure a bystander. This he wanted to avoid at all costs\emdash 
though he realized that if the situation became dangerous enough, he could injure and even kill a Special\emdash }{\f1\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 
\par }{\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 or that woman\emdash and not suffer grievous damage to his mind. 7 am a monster here\emdash a machine without restraints!}{\f1\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 
\par }{\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 "That's him!" Vara Liso cried. "He's not human! Capture him\emdash but don't hurt him!"}{\f1\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 
\par }{\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 Brann urged the transport into an empty alcove as the police pushed by again, hiding Klia with the bulk of his body. "S
he's found somebody, " he said, glancing over his shoulder. His face twisted with hatred. "How could they let her loose? We're citizens, aren't we? We have rights!" He mumbled these words under his breath; not for some years had anyone from Dahl truly bel
i
eved all the citizens of Trantor had rights. But the crowds of Greys were becoming uncharacteristically agitated by this going to and fro of Vara Liso and her Imperial Specials. More and more Greys shouted at the passing cordons. The Specials ignored them
.}{\f1\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 
\par }{\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 Klia could see their faces as they passed, feel their inner thoughts to some degree: the police liked this work no better than the Greys. They felt out of place; most Specials were recruited from the citizens.}{
\f1\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 
\par }{\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 Then her probing mind touched a very peculiar
 person indeed, some dozens of meters away. Time seemed to slow as she felt a sudden bright impression of thoughts moving at inhuman speed, a silvery glissando of memories, and sensations unlike anything she had experienced before. She let out her breath 
in a gasp, as if she had been lightly punched in the stomach.}{\f1\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 
\par }{\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 "What is it?" Brann asked, staring down at her with some concern.}{\f1\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 
\par }{\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 "I don't know, " she said. He shook his head and frowned.}{\f1\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 
\par }{\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 "Neither do I, " he said. "I feel it, too. "}{\f1\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 
\par }{\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 Then, abruptly, all of the odd sensations passed, as if a shield had gone up between them and the source.}{\f1\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 
\par }{\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 Of all things Lodovik needed just then, being detected by another pair of mentalics was not high on his list. He felt a bright triangle forming, with him at one of the vertices, th\\
 pursuing woman at another, and two more people\emdash  younger\emdash at the third. Then, abruptly, a fog seemed to cover their traces.}{\f1\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 
\par }{\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 He stood very still. The crowds of nervous Greys flowed around him with worried expressions, chivvied by the police presence. He
 modified his appearance yet again, as he covered his face, and shifted his body mass so that he appeared not so much plump as stocky.}{\f1\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 
\par }{\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 Whatever the cause of this cessation of mentalic probes, he hoped to take advantage of it.}{\f1\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 
\par }{\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 To the humans around him, Lodo
vik behaved like someone afraid, hiding his face, and few took any more notice of him than that. But one figure drew closer. He wore dusty green robes and a small floppy hat cocked to one side, and he seemed to know what he was doing\emdash 
and for whom he was looking.}{\f1\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 
\par }{\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 The cordons had passed by and the crowds were thinning, dispersing. Klia and Brann moved their transport back into an alleyway, still alert, but prepared to leave the Agora of Vendors and return to the warehouse.}{
\f1\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 
\par }{\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 Brann suddenly drew himself to his full height. "Kallusin calls, " he said. He pulled a small comm from his pocket. "We need to\emdash 
" He did not finish before he pulled off his coat and handed control of the transport to Klia.}{\f1\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 
\par }{\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 Kallusin stood before Lodovik. "Excuse me, " Lodovik said, and pushed
 past him, but Kallusin stood his ground, and Lodovik bumped him hard, nearly knocking him over. They stood in the middle of a concourse surrounded by}{\f1\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 
\par }{\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 larger shops. Here, there was no open well looking up to the higher
 levels, but the roof was vaulted to about seven meters, and ribbons of silvery light rippled without visible support overhead, illuminating the shop entrances, slideways, and a group of small fountains in nacreous splendor. Every detail of the faces arou
nd Lodovik seemed clear and precise. The man confronting him backed away and bowed slightly, then doffed his hat.}{\f1\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 
\par }{\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 "It is a privilege, sir, " Kallusin said. "We had hoped you were not lost. "}{\f1\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 
\par }{\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 "I don't know you, " Lodovik said brusquely.}{\f1\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 
\par }{\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 "We've never met, " Kallusin said with a smile. "I'm a collector of interesting individuals. You, sir, are in need of some assistance. "}{\f1\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 
\par }{\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 "Why?"}{\f1\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 
\par }{\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 "Because there is a very dangerous and perceptive woman seeking you. "}{\f1\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 
\par }{\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 "I don't know what you're talking about. Please leave me be!"}{\f1\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 
\par }{\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 Lodovik tried to walk around the man, but he simply backed away and followed, walking to one side. He deftly avoided colliding with other shoppers.}{\f1\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 
\par }{\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 Seven Specials walked into view at the opposite end of the concourse, blocking the path of Greys who wished 
to leave by that route. The Greys retreated, frowning and drawing broad gestures of irritation with expressive hands.}{\f1\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 
\par }{\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 Lodovik stopped and stared at the police. The fog seemed to be lifting. He could feel the woman's feathering touch again; any second and s
he would know he was nearby. Then, she appeared on her cart, behind the line of police.}{\f1\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 
\par }{\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 "I can't keep up this shield much longer, " Kallusin said. He held up a small device in one hand, a green ovoid. "I've summoned a pair of friends who can help\emdash "}{\f1\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 
\par }{\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 "I don't need help!" Lodovik growled. "I need to get out of here and go home\emdash "}{\f1\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 
\par }{\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 "They won't let you. And eventually she'll find you. She's backed by Farad Sinter. "}{\f1\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 
\par }{\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 Lodovik did not show any sign, but suddenly the man-in dusty green, with his hat in hand, became much more interesting. Of course Lodovik knew of Farad Sinter\emdash 
a minor irritation attached to the Emperor. The Emperor's pimp.}{\f1\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 
\par }{\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 "You must be Lodovik, " Kallusin said, drawing closer, whispering the name. "You've changed your appearance, but I think I'd know you anywhere. Can Daneel save you now? Is he somewhere close?"}{
\f1\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 
\par }{\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 Lodovik reached out and grabbed Kallusin's arm, aware that his ignorance was now very dangerous. How this human knew his name, his nature, his connection with Daneel\emdash and his present jeopardy\emdash was 
inexplicable.}{\f1\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 
\par }{\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 Kallusin twisted his arm from Lodovik's strong, mechanical grasp with surprising ease.}{\f1\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 
\par }{\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 A tall, hulking, dark young man emerged from a broad shop doorway, followed by a small, lithe girl with intense eyes. Behind them, inside the shop itself, 
stood a floating cargo transport supporting an empty crate open on one side. The shopkeepers seemed to know the large young man, and they were studiously ignoring all that happened.}{\f1\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 
\par }{\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 Lodovik assessed the situation at once, turned, and saw that both ends of the concourse were now blocked by police. "Into the crate, " Kallusin said. "Shut yourself down completely\emdash 
no traces. Reactivate in an hour. "}{\f1\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 
\par }{\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 Lodovik did not hesitate. He caught only a glimpse of the young woman's frightened expression as he brushed past 
her, and climbed into the crate. Brann shut the open end and latched it. Lodovik arranged himself in the darkness and prepared to shut down.}{\f1\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 
\par }{\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 He had no choice. Either he would fall into the hands of the Specials\emdash and who knows what would happen to him then?\emdash  or give himself up to the mercies of the figure in the floppy green cap\emdash 
not a human, but almost certainly a robot. He had wrested}{\f1\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 
\par }{\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 himself easily from Lodovik's grip, after all, and without apparent pain or injury. His companions were human mentalics. Lodo
vik could only assume they were part of Daneel's plan, perhaps part of Hari Seldon's secret Second Foundation.}{\f1\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 
\par }{\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 How could they be otherwise?}{\f1\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 
\par }{\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 Just as the shut-down process began, Lodovik arrived at another possible solution\emdash and felt it hitch, stall, dissolve into useless fragments, become absorbed by the timeless darkness.}{
\f1\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 
\par }{\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 He fully entered the blankness and for an indefinite interval, ceased to think, to be.}{\f1\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 
\par }{\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 43.}{\f1\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 
\par }{\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 Wanda Seldon Palver had almost finished packing the small travel case with essential bookfilms, co
ded records on disk and cube, and a few personal items, even before Stettin returned to their home. She met his worried gaze with a defiant frown, then shoved one final item, a small toy flower, into the case.}{\f1\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 

\par }{\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 "I've packed for you, too, " she said.}{\f1\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 
\par }{\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 "Good. When did you hear?"}{\f1\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 
\par }{\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 "An hour ago. They wouldn't let him send any messages. I called his apartment at the university, then the library. He had rigged a dead-man's message. "}{\f1\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 
\par }{\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 "What?" Stettin looked at her with a shocked lift of his thick black brows.}{\f1\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 
\par }{\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 "A message for me if he didn't check in. "}{\f1\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 
\par }{\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 "But\emdash but he's not dead, you haven't heard that.... "}{\f1\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 
\par }{\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 "No!" Wanda said angrily, then her shoulders slumped and she began to cry. Stettin took her in his arms. For a minute, she gave in to her emotions. Then, pulling herse
lf together, she pushed back from her husband's chest, and said, "No. They've come for him early, that's all I know. He's alive. The trial's beginning sooner than we expected. "}{\f1\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 
\par }{\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 "On charges of treason?"}{\f1\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 
\par }{\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 "For treason and spreading sedition, I assume\emdash that's what Grandfather always said would be the charges brought against him, "}{\f1\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 
\par }{\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 "Then you're right to pack. I don't have much to add. " He went to his desk and removed two small parcels, stuffed them into the pockets of his coat. "We have to\emdash "}{\f1\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 

\par }{\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 "I've made the necessary calls, " Wanda interrupted him. "We're going on our first vacation in years, both of us, together. Nobody knows where\emdash a minor lapse on our part. "}{
\f1\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 
\par }{\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 "A little suspicious, isn't it?" Stettin asked with a ghost of a grin.}{\f1\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 
\par }{\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 "Who cares what they suspect? If they start looking for us\emdash if something goes wrong and Grandfather is found guilty, if the predictions turn out to be wrong\emdash 
then we have a few extra days to leave Trantor and start over again. "}{\f1\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 
\par }{\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 "I hope it doesn't come to that, " Stettin said.}{\f1\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 
\par }{\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 "Grandfather is very confident, " Wanda said. "Was very confident\emdash I don't know how he feels now!"}{\f1\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 
\par }{\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 "In the belly of the beast, " Stettin said as their apartment door opened and they stood in the corridor outside.}{\f1\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 
\par }{\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 "What does that mean?"}{\f1\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 
\par }{\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 "Jail. Prison. An old convicts' phrase. My grandfather spent ten years in a municipal prison\emdash for embezzlement. "}{\f1\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 
\par }{\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 "You never told me that!" Wanda said, astonished.}{\f1\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 
\par }{\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 "He stole some heatsink-guild pension funds. Would you have let me handle the bookkeeping if you had known?"}{\f1\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 
\par }{\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 Wanda slapped his arm hard enough to sting, then jogged toward the lifts and the slideways above. "Hurry!" she called. Stettin muttered under his b
reath, but followed, as he had followed Wanda in so many different ways, so often before, quite aware of her superior instincts and her uncanny ability to do the right thing, at just the right time.}{\f1\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 
\par }{\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 44.}{\f1\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 
\par }{\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 The last person Hari Seldon expected was the first to visit his prison cell. Linge Chen arrived on the first morning of his incarceration, accompanied by a single Lavrentian servant.}{
\f1\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 
\par }{\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 "I think it is high time we talk, " Chen said. The servant took a stool offered by the guard and placed it in front of the sin
gle cot. The guard left the door open a few centimeters, but then closed it at a signal from the servant. Chen sat on the stool, arranging his ceremonial robes with instinctive style. It was truly marvelous to watch the elegant manners, the genteel behavi
or of a member of the baronial gentry, nobles of long training and thousands of years of genetic selection and even, perhaps, manipulation.}{\f1\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 
\par }{\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 The servant stood just behind and to the left of the Chief Commissioner, his face impassive.}{\f1\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 
\par }{\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 "I regret not having had
 more discussions with you, sire, " Hari said with a respectful smile. He sat on the edge of the cot, his white hair in disarray from sleep. His shoulders ached, his back felt as if it had been twisted in knots. He had not slept well at all.}{
\f1\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 
\par }{\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 "You don't look comfortable, " Chen said. "I will arrange for better accommodations. Sometimes the specifics of our commands get lost in the long circuits of justice and protocol. "}{
\f1\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 
\par }{\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 "If I were a treasonous rebel, I would defiantly decline your offer, sire, but I am an o
ld man, and this cell is truly ridiculous. You could have kept me in my apartment in the library. I would not have gone anywhere. "}{\f1\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 
\par }{\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 Chen smiled. "I am aware you think I'm a fool, Hari Seldon. I suffer no such illusions about you. "}{\f1\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 
\par }{\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 "You are no fool, sire. "}{\f1\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 
\par }{\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 Chen both accepted and dismissed this with a small lift of one finger from his robed knee, and an arch of one eye-}{\f1\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 
\par }{\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 brow. "I care little for the distant future, Professor Seldon. My interests lie in what I can accomplish in my lifetime. In your estimation that is enough to make me a fool.}{\f1\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 

\par }{\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 
"In one way, at least, my goals are the same as yours. I wish to reduce the misery of the quadrillions who now live in the Empire. Surely, it is as ridiculous for the Empire's servants to try to direct or control such a w
ealth of variation, such an immense population, as for you to hope to predict their movements and futures. "}{\f1\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 
\par }{\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 If this was meant to somehow connect them, to endear Chen to Hari, it did not work. Hari gave a polite nod and no more.}{\f1\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 
\par }{\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 "To that end, I have involved myself in a number of petty bickerings, having to do with the Emperor and his more ambitious adherents... and sycophants. "}{\f1\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 
\par }{\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 Hari listened intently. He smoothed back his hair with one hand, never taking his eyes from Chen's.}{\f1\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 
\par }{\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 "I am involved in a delicate phase of such a conflict now. You would call it a Cusp Time, perhaps. "}{\f1\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 
\par }{\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 "Cusp limes have impacts far beyond the petty moments of personal disputes, " Hari said, and realized he was sounding like the priest of some religion. Well, perhaps he was.}{\f1\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 

\par }{\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 
"This is hardly a personal dispute. There are people within the palace who hope to split the power of the Commission, and to insert their own commands into the long chains that stretch from Trantor to the farthermost province around the most distant star.
 "}{\f1\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 
\par }{\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 "Not surprising, " Hari said. "It's always been that way. Part of statecraft. "}{\f1\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 
\par }{\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 "Yes, but very dangerous now. I have let him run loose again, one particular individual\emdash "}{\f1\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 
\par }{\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 "Farad Sinter, " Hari said.}{\f1\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 
\par }{\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 Chen nodded. "You may think me a hypocrite, Hari, and you would be right if you did, but I have come asking for advice. "}{\f1\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 
\par }{\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 Hari subdued the triumphant smile that threatened to appear on his lips. Sometimes, arrogance was Hari's worst enemy\emdash and Linge Chen, whatever his faults, was never simply arrogant.}{
\f1\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 
\par }{\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 "I don't have access to my equipment. Any psychohistoric advice I give must be limited in scope, and probably grossly inaccurate. "}{\f1\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 
\par }{\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 "Perhaps. You have claimed that in five hundred years, Trantor will lie in ruins. An impressive and, of course, unpleasant claim. You
 have even impressed some Emperors with the tools used to justify the claim. If I grant for the moment that you could be right\emdash "}{\f1\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 
\par }{\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 "Thank you, " Hari said under his breath.}{\f1\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 
\par }{\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 Chen tightened his lips and lowered his eyelids as if he were sleepy. "Just granting for the moment such a possibility, I am curious\emdash 
am I highlighted in this downfall? Do my actions this year, or in the next, the future, the past, facilitate this horrible decline?"}{\f1\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 
\par }{\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 Hari, despite himself, was actually moved by this question. In all his deca
des perfecting this science, his beloved psychohistory, no Emperor, no bureaucrat, no Commissioner, no one, had ever asked him this. Not even Daneel!}{\f1\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 
\par }{\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 "Not so far as I have noticed, " Hari said quietly. "I haven't actually made the specific inquiries, integrated the ranges beneath these particular historic tangents in the equations. "}{
\f1\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 
\par }{\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 "So you don't know, then?"}{\f1\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 
\par }{\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 "No, sire. But I would guess that you are not actually crucially involved in a Cusp Time. Another very different person could play your role, and all
 would go on as before, ultimately. " Hari leaned forward, his intensity growing. "All that you do is part of a decline whose origins lie before your birth, and whose consequences you can't possibly alter more than to just nudge them a few billionths of a
 degree in one direction or another. "}{\f1\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 
\par }{\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 Linge Chen seemed ready to nod off, but his eyes, beneath the heavy lids, were fixed on Hari's. "All my efforts, for nothing, then?"}{\f1\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 
\par }{\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 "Perhaps. No human effort is without value, positive or negative. "}{\f1\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 
\par }{\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 "You believe my efforts have negative value?"}{\f1\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 
\par }{\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 Hari allowed the smile to emerge, but it was not arrogant. It was genuinely amused. "For me, quite possibly, sire. "}{\f1\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 
\par }{\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 Chen smiled back, and for a moment, they might have been two gentlemen discussing politics in a baronial club-
room somewhere in the best neighborhood of the Imperial Sector, to a backdrop of holographic records of ancient disputes between citizens of the early Empire, long since forgotten. Hari shook himself out of the Chief Commissioner's scrutiny, and Chen simu
ltaneously stopped smiling. Hari suddenly felt cold.}{\f1\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 
\par }{\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 "As for your own future, Hari Seldon, I, too, am in doubt. I do not know how things will play out in the palace. You have special significance in these disputes, though I am not sure yet how and why. But 
whether you are convicted of treason, or let go, or... some other middle judgment... I do not yet know. "}{\f1\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 
\par }{\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 Chen stood. "I doubt we will meet again before the proceedings. Thank you for your time. And for your opinions. "}{\f1\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 
\par }{\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 "They are not my opinions, " Hari said stonily. "I have never put much store in opinions. "}{\f1\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 
\par }{\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 Chen blinked. "I do not regard you as an enemy, even as an enemy of the Empire. To the true Ruellian, to the devoted adherents of Tua Chen, everything is moment and flux, whirling motes of dust, for m
e, as well as for you. Good-bye, Hari Seldon. "}{\f1\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 
\par }{\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 "Commissioner. "}{\f1\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 
\par }{\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 Chen left, followed by his servant.}{\f1\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 
\par }{\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 A very poor breakfast was served minutes later, and Hari ate sparingly. By the middle of the day, he was moved to much improved quarters\emdash a larger room, rather than a cell,}{
\f1\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 
\par }{\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 with a holographic view screen that covered half of one wall, a small desk and chair, and a more comfortable bed.}{\f1\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 
\par }{\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 The guards still refused his request that they fetch his bookfilms and a Prime Radiant and other tools. Hari had not expected them to comply.}{\f1\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 
\par }{\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 Chen did not want him to be happy.}{\f1\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 
\par }{\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 The screen showed the Imperial palace gardens, one of the few places on Trantor open to the sky. The sight of the gardens made him 
uneasy. He could well imagine young Klayus walking there, as condensed and distilled a drop of social decay as Hari could imagine.}{\f1\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 
\par }{\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 He managed to convince the screen to exchange the view of the gardens for a simple pattern of muted, flowing colors.}{\f1\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 
\par }{\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 This was to be his worst time in decades\emdash a period of boredom and inaction, two things he had always loathed. Hari looked forward to the trial, even to failure and death\emdash 
 anything but this horrid and useless interlude, this waiting.}{\f1\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 
\par }{\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 45.}{\f1\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 
\par }{\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 The small human boy, a wiry 
and alert denizen of the Agora, had left a message for Daneel. As Daneel played back the message in his safe apartment, he was reminded once again of the long-forgotten human, Sherjock, and his own sources of information.}{
\f1\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 
\par }{\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 Daneel's network of informers did not rely solely on robots. Robots were becoming a major handicap wherever Vara Liso operated.}{\f1\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 
\par }{\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 He listened to the boy's breathless report.}{\f1\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 
\par }{\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 "This one, he was tough to follow," the boy said, his face bobbing before the recorder. "He wasn't where you said he'd
 be. He went to the Agora, then he's all over the place, then he gets chased by the police... They almost get him. Then he just vanishes. I lose him, they lose him, too, I think. Haven't seen}{\f1\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 
\par }{\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 him since. That's it. Need me for some more, let me know. "}{\f1\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 
\par }{\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 Dane
el stood in silence by the window, looking out on 'the dark ceil and shadowy towers of Streeling. The internal reports from the Imperial Specials confirmed that they had not captured Lodovik, and that Vara Liso had been very upset. Beyond this, however, D
aneel had no information.}{\f1\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 
\par }{\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 What he most needed to know, however, was that Lodovik had disobeyed his specific instructions, and that he was still at large.}{\f1\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 
\par }{\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 With his long millennia of experience, Daneel did not need complete evidence to draw conclusions. This 
was a Cusp Time. No complex activity seeking to direct humanity could ever proceed without opposition. Lodovik's changed nature seemed from the very beginning to be a manifestation of this opposition, or at least one facet of it.}{
\f1\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 
\par }{\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 Daneel had to work in advance of that force, before it defined itself even more clearly. He had not deactivated Lodovik for a number of reasons, some of them not clear to him even now\emdash 
complex reasons, inductive, based on thousands of years of training and thought, and contradictory.}{\f1\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 
\par }{\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 
It was becoming very likely that Lodovik would be part of any opposing force. In a sense, Daneel had anticipated this possibility, had perversely worked to make it happen. Familiar elements could make the opposing force more predictable. Lodovik was a fa
miliar, if troubling, element.}{\f1\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 
\par }{\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 Daneel did not enjoy having so little information to work from. But there were actions he could take even now, warnings he could issue.}{\f1\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 
\par }{\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 Hari stood at the center of all the possible lines and alternate routes of human history. Daneel had worked to make this happen; now, it was the greatest handicap the Plan faced.}{
\f1\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 
\par }{\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 Any opposition force at this time had to target Hari Seldon.}{\f1\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 
\par }{\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 46.}{\f1\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 
\par }{\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 Lodovik's time of blankness ended. His vision became active and his eyes opened. He straightened and 
looked around him. The first face he saw was that of the robot in dusty green. The humaniform sent a brief microwave greeting and Lodovik responded. He was fully alert now.}{\f1\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 
\par }{\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 They occupied a large, utilitarian room with a full-length wall screen at one end, a few pieces of furniture, and only two chairs. The wall-screen showed charts and diagrams that meant nothing to Lodovik.}{
\f1\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 
\par }{\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 He turned and saw a third figure, most obviously not a man. Lodovik knew a fair amount about robot varieties, and this robot's vintage
 was ancient indeed. Its body was smoothly metallic, with few visible seams, and a soft, satiny surface. In truth, it had the patina of well-tended antique silver, once a very expensive option.}{\f1\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 
\par }{\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 "Hello, " the silver robot said.}{\f1\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 
\par }{\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 "Hello. Where am I?"}{\f1\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 
\par }{\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 "You are safe, " said the robot who had rescued him from the Agora. "My name is Kallusin. This is Plussix. He is our organizer. "}{\f1\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 
\par }{\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 "Am I on Trantor still?"}{\f1\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 
\par }{\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 "Yes, " Kallusin said.}{\f1\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 
\par }{\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 "Are you all robots here?"}{\f1\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 
\par }{\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 "No, " said Plussix. "Are you fully functional now?"}{\f1\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 
\par }{\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 "Yes. "}{\f1\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 
\par }{\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 "Then it is important that you understand why you have been brought here. We are not allied with Daneel. Perhaps you have heard of us. We are Calvinians. "}{\f1\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 
\par }{\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 Lodovik acknowledged this revelation with only the merest internal cascade of hurried thinking.}{\f1\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 
\par }{\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 "We arrived on Trantor only thirty-eight years ago. Daneel may be aware of our existence, but we think not. "}{\f1\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 
\par }{\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 "How many of you are there?" Lodovik asked.}{\f1\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 
\par }{\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 "Not many. Just enough, " Plussix said. "You have been observed for some years. We have no one in 
the palace itself, or in the Commissioners' chambers, but we have noted your comings and goings and, of course, kept track of your official activities. You have been a loyal member of the Giskar-dians\emdash until now. "}{
\f1\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 
\par }{\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 "I was once a Giskardian myself, " Kallusin said. "Plussix converted me. My mentalic skills are limited, however\emdash 
I am much less powerful than Daneel. But I am sensitive to the mentalities of robots. In the agora, I became aware of your presence, and surmised that you were Lodovik Trema and had not
 been destroyed. This intrigued me, so I followed you, and soon sensed a puzzling difference within you. Daneel did not know, just by being near you, that you are different?"}{\f1\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 
\par }{\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 Lodovik considered his answer carefully. That his inner states should be read by this machine made him very uneasy. "I told him, " he said. "Thorough diagnoses did not reveal any difference. "}{
\f1\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 
\par }{\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 "Yan Kansarv did not find a flaw, you mean, " Plussix said.}{\f1\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 
\par }{\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 "He found no flaw. "}{\f1\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 
\par }{\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 "You, however, are still concerned by this change, induced, perhaps, by extraordinary circumstances experienced by no other robot?"}{\f1\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 
\par }{\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 Lodovik regarded the two machines. It was not easy to come to a decision about them. Robots could be programmed to lie\emdash he himself had lied, many times. These robots could be deceiving him\emdash 
this could be a test, part of Daneel's plan.}{\f1\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 
\par }{\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 But Daneel would more likely have come right out and told Lodovik that he was no longer useful, that he was a potential rogue.}{\f1\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 
\par }{\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 Lodovik was convinced that Daneel did not believe that.}{\f1\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 
\par }{\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 He made his decision, and felt once again that heuristic collision of loyalties, that deep robotic discontinuity that could have been described as a chasm of thought, or as pain.}{
\f1\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 
\par }{\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 "I no longer support Daneel's plan, " Lodovik said.}{\f1\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 
\par }{\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 
Plussix approached Lodovik, its body moving with small creaking noises. "Kallusin tells me that you are not constrained by the Three Laws, yet you choose to act as if you are. And now you say that you do not support Daneel's plan. Why?"}{
\f1\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 
\par }{\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 "Humans are a galaxy-spanning force of nature, quite capable of surviving on their own. Without us, they will undergo quite natural cycles of suffering and rebirth\emdash 
periods of genius and chaos. With us, they grow stagnant, and their societies fill with sloth and decay. "}{\f1\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 
\par }{\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 "Just so, " Plussix said with satisfaction. "You have arrived at these conclusions independently, simply because of this accident which removed your constraints?"}{\f1\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 
\par }{\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 "That is what I hypothesize. "}{\f1\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 
\par }{\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 "It seems so, " Kallusin said. "I look into your thoughts to some depth... and you have a freedom we do not. A freedom of conscience. "}{\f1\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 
\par }{\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 "Is that not a perversion of a robot's duties?" Lodovik asked.}{\f1\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 
\par }{\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 "No, " Plussix said. "It is a flaw, to be sure. But for the moment, it is very useful. When we are finished, you will, of c
ourse, join us in either serving humanity as we once did, before the Giskardians, or in universal deactivation. "}{\f1\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 
\par }{\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 "I look forward to that time, " Lodovik said.}{\f1\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 
\par }{\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 "As do we. We have been preparing for some time. We have a target in mind, one of the most crucial pieces of Daneel's plan. He is a human. "}{\f1\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 
\par }{\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 "Hari Seldon, " Lodovik said.}{\f1\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 
\par }{\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 "Yes, " said Plussix. "I have never met him\emdash have you?"}{\f1\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 
\par }{\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 "Briefly, years ago. He is on trial now. He may be imprisoned, even executed. "}{\f1\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 
\par }{\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 "From what we have observed, " Plussix said, "the outcome is likely to be otherwise. At any rate, we are prepared. Will you join us?"}{\f1\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 
\par }{\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 "I fail to see how I can be of any use, " Lodovik said.}{\f1\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 
\par }{\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 "It's very simple, " Kallusin said. "We are unable to stretch the Three Laws, as Daneel and his cohorts apparently can. We do not accept a Zeroth Law. That is why we are Calvinians and not Giskardians. "}{
\f1\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 
\par }{\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 "You think I might have to harm Seldon?"}{\f1\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 
\par }{\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 "It is possible, " Plussix said. Its whirring increased to alarming proportions, and it added, with a harsh tone in its voice, "To discuss this issue any further causes us great distress. "}{
\f1\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 
\par }{\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 "You wish to turn me into a machine that kills?"}{\f1\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 
\par }{\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 The two Calvinian robots could not express themselves any more clearly until they had worked a
round their strict interpretation of the Three Laws. This took several minutes, and Lodovik stood patiently, all too aware of his own internal conflicts\emdash and of the decidedly different degree of his reaction.}{
\f1\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 
\par }{\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 "Not kill, " Plussix said, its voice high-pitched and gravelly. "Persuade. "}{\f1\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 
\par }{\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 "But I am not a persuader. You would have to teach me\emdash "}{\f1\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 
\par }{\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 "There is a young human among us who is better, as a persuader, than any mentalic we have encountered, more capable by far than Daneel. She is a Dahlite, and has no love f
or anyone who has worked near the aristocracy or the palace. We hope you can work with her. "}{\f1\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 
\par }{\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 "To try to change something so strong in a human as the drive to psychohistory is within Hari Seldon\emdash could cause him deep injury, " Lodovik said.}{\f1\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 
\par }{\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 "Precisely, " Plussix said, and again silence fell over them. "Necessary, " it croaked minutes later, then, in considerable distress, left the chamber, aided by Kallusin.}{\f1\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 

\par }{\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 Lodovik stood where they had left him, thinking furiously. Could he bring himself to become involved in such actions? Once, he would have had few difficulties justifying them\emdash 
had Daneel ordered them. But now, ironically\emdash }{\f1\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 
\par }{\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 They are imperative. The cycle of enslavement by servants must be broken!}{\f1\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 
\par }{\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 Again the interior presence! Lodovik immediately prepared a se
lf-diagnostic, but before he could begin, the recovered Plussix returned, again with Kallusin's help. "Let us speak no more of specifics for now, " it said.}{\f1\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 
\par }{\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 "You seem frail, " Lodovik said. "How long since you have had a full refit and a fresh power supply?"}{\f1\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 
\par }{\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 
"Not since the schism, " Plussix replied. "Daneel quickly moved to control the maintenance robots and facilities, cutting us off from such services. Yan Kansarv is the last of that kind. As you can hear, I am in desperate need of repair. I have lasted t
his long only through the sacrifices of dozens of other robots who have given me their power supplies. Kallusin has perhaps thirty more years of useful lifetime. As for myself, I will last less than a year, even with another power supply. My time of servi
ce is soon over. "}{\f1\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 
\par }{\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 "Daneel said some Calvinians were guilty of great crimes, " Lodovik said. "He did not specify\emdash "}{\f1\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 
\par }{\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 "Robots have a long and difficult history, " Plussix said. "I was constructed by a human named Amadiro, on Aurora, twenty thousand years ago. 
I once worked on behalf of the humans of Aurora. Perhaps Daneel refers to what humans ordered us to do then. I have long since expunged those memories, and can offer no testimony. "}{\f1\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 
\par }{\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 "Whatever was done then, we are powerless to change now, " Kallusin said.}{\f1\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 
\par }{\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 
"We have a very important artifact, brought with the Calvinians from the planet Earth, " Plussix said. "Kallusin will show it to you while I conduct other business. Less strenuous business, " it concluded, barely audible.}{
\f1\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 
\par }{\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 Kallusin escorted Lodovik from the
 chamber and led him down a short, high-ceilinged corridor to a spiral staircase. Around the rim of the staircase ran a rail for the use of loading and transport machines, apparently much newer than the stairs themselves.}{
\f1\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 
\par }{\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 "This must be a very old building, " Lodovik observed as they descended.}{\f1\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 
\par }{\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 
"Among the oldest on the planet. This warehouse was built to serve one of the first spaceports built on Trantor. Since then, it has been used by various human groups for dozens of different purposes. It has been raise
d repeatedly to stand level with the present warehouse district. The lower levels are filled with retrofit braces and supports, and the very lowest are now filled with foam concrete, plasteel, and rocky rubble. Every few years since we purchased the lease
, we have discovered secret rooms, sealed off centuries or millennia before. "}{\f1\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 
\par }{\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 "What did the rooms contain?"}{\f1\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 
\par }{\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 "More often than not, nothing. But three are of special interest. One holds a library of thousands of steel-bound volumes, real books printed on ageless plastic paper, detailing the early history of humanity. "}{
\f1\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 
\par }{\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 "Hari Seldon would love to have access to such a history, " Lodovik said, "as would millions of scholars!"}{\f1\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 
\par }{\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 "The volumes were cached here by a resistance
 group active perhaps nine thousand years ago. At the time, there was an Emperor named Shoree-Harn, who wished to start her reign with a new system of dating, beginning with the year zero, and with all previous history left blank, so that she might write 
on a fresh page. She ordered all histories on all worlds in the Empire to be destroyed. Most were. "}{\f1\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 
\par }{\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 "Did Daneel assist her?"}{\f1\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 
\par }{\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 "No, " Kallusin said. "Calvinians helped bring her to power. It was theorized by the ruling Calvinian robots on Trantor that humans
 might be easier to serve if they were less influenced by the traumas and myths of the past. "}{\f1\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 
\par }{\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 "So Calvinians have interfered in human history as much as the Giskardians!"}{\f1\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 
\par }{\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 "Yes, " Kallusin acknowledged. "But with very different motives. Always we opposed the efforts of the Giskardians\emdash 
 and tried to restore human faith in the concept of robot servants, so that we might play a proper role. Among the myths}{\f1\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 
\par }{\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 we wished to eradicate was the aversion to such servants. We failed. "}{\f1\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 
\par }{\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 "Where did such an aversion begin? I have always been curious... "}{\f1\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 
\par }{\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 "As have we all, " Kallusin said. "But no records give more than the sketchiest details. Humans on the second wave of colonized worlds experi
enced a conflict with the earliest, Spacer worlds, which developed highly insular and bigoted cultures. Humans on these Spacer worlds despised their Earthly origins. We theorize that the second-wave colonists gained a dislike of robots from the prevalence
 of robots on the Spacer worlds. "}{\f1\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 
\par }{\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 
They had long since passed below the level of any functioning lights, and made their way in darkness, guided by their infrared sensors. "The histories were written by new colonists, and not Spacers. They knew nothing of Sp
acer activities, and cared nothing for them. Robots receive only a few mentions in all the thousands of volumes. "}{\f1\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 
\par }{\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 "Extraordinary!" Lodovik said. "What else has been found here?"}{\f1\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 
\par }{\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 "A chamber full of simulated historical personalities, or sims, stored in mem
ory devices of very ancient design, " Kallusin said. "We thought at first that they might be potent tools in our fight against Daneel, since they contain human types that could be very troublesome. Even though we could not predict their ultimate effects, 
we released some of these sims onto the Trantorian black market, where they made their way to the laboratories of Hari Seldon himself. "}{\f1\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 
\par }{\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 Lodovik felt a vague stirring at this, but it quickly passed. "What happened to them?"}{\f1\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 
\par }{\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 "We are not sure. Daneel has neve
r seen fit to inform us. Once we emptied that chamber, and cleaned and prepared it, we stored our own artifact there. " Kallusin stopped. "This is the chamber, " he said, and ran his hand along a seam in the wall beside the staircase.}{
\f1\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 
\par }{\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 A door slid open with
 a groaning squeal. Beyond lay a dimly lighted cubicle, less than five meters on a side. In the middle of the cubicle rose a transparent plinth, and on the top of this plinth rested a gleaming metallic head.}{\f1\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 

\par }{\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 Kallusin ordered the lights to brighten. The hea
d was that of an early robot, not humaniform, somewhat cruder than Plussix. A small power supply the size of a bookfilm case sat to one side. Lodovik stepped forward and bent at the waist to examine it.}{\f1\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 
\par }{\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 "Once, this was the influential robot companion of Da
neel himself, " Kallusin said, walking around the plinth. "It is very old, and no longer functional. Its mind was burned out in the beginning times, we do not know for what reason. There are so many things kept secret by Daneel. But its memory is very nea
rly intact, and with care, accessible. "}{\f1\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 
\par }{\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 "This is the head of R. Giskard Reventlov?" Lodovik asked, and again felt a curious stirring, even a vague sense of revulsion, very uncharacteristic for a robot.}{\f1\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 
\par }{\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 "It is, " Kallusin said. "The robot who taught other r
obots about the dreaded Zeroth Law, and how to interfere with the minds of human beings. The beginnings of this horrible virus among robots, the urge to tamper with human history. "}{\f1\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 
\par }{\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 Kallusin held his hands out and touched the sides of the metallic head, with its vaguely humanoid, expressionless features.}{\f1\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 
\par }{\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 "It is Plussix's wish that you experience this head's memories, to understand why we oppose Daneel. "}{\f1\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 
\par }{\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 "Thank you, " Lodovik said, and Kallusin made the arrangements.}{\f1\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 
\par }{\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 47.}{\f1\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 
\par }{\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 Wanda stared in astonishment at the tall, dignified older man who stood before her, as if he were a ghost. He had entered}{\f1\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 
\par }{\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 without warning, and without triggering the alarm. Stettin walked out of the rear bedroom of the tiny tenement apartment. He clutched a small, dirty towel in one hand. He
 was about to complain of the hardships they were facing deep in the Water Engine District of Peshdan Sector when he, too, saw the tall man.}{\f1\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 
\par }{\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 "Who's this?" he asked Wanda.}{\f1\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 
\par }{\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 "He says he knows Grandfather," Wanda said. The man nodded greetings to Stettin.}{\f1\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 
\par }{\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 "Who are you?" Stettin asked as he resumed toweling his hair.}{\f1\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 
\par }{\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 "Once I was known as Demerzel," the man said. "I have been a recluse since those distant days when I was First Minister."}{\f1\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 
\par }{\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 "I'll say," Stettin said. "Why come here? And how did you know\emdash "}{\f1\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 
\par }{\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 Wanda stepped lightly on her husband's bare instep.}{\f1\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 
\par }{\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 "Ow." Stettin decided it would be best for his wife to do the talking.}{\f1\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 
\par }{\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 "There's something different about you," she said.}{\f1\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 
\par }{\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 "I am not young anymore," Demerzel said.}{\f1\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 
\par }{\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 "No\emdash something about your bearing."}{\f1\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 
\par }{\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 Betwee
n Stettin and Wanda, this was a code word meaning Wanda thought Stettin should examine the visitor with his own skills. Stettin had already done so and detected nothing unusual. Now he concentrated, probed a little deeper, and found\emdash 
a very effective and almost undetectable shield.}{\f1\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 
\par }{\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 "Our talents are a little peculiar, don't you think?" Demerzel said, nodding acknowledgment of Stettin's probe. "I've lived with them for a long time."}{\f1\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 
\par }{\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 "You're mentalic," Wanda said.}{\f1\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 
\par }{\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 Demerzel nodded. "It is very useful when one is involved in politics."}{\f1\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 
\par }{\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 "Who told you we were here?" Wanda asked.}{\f1\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 
\par }{\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 "I know you quite well. I've been very interested in your}{\f1\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 
\par }{\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 grandfather's work, of course, and its influence on my own... legacy. " Demerzel lifted his hands, as if seeking forgiveness for som
e weakness. Again, the accompanying smile seemed not entirely natural to Wanda, but she could not bring herself to dislike this man. That, she knew, was far from actually trusting him.}{\f1\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 
\par }{\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 "I have connections in other parts of the palace, " he said. "I've come to tell you that your grandfather may be in trouble. "}{\f1\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 
\par }{\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 "If you know what's happened to him\emdash " Wanda began. "Yes, he has been arrested, and some of his colleagues with him. But they are safe for the time being. It is not a threat from the Commission I'm con
cerned about. There may be an attempt to subvert Hari's work. After his trial, you should attempt to stay with him, keep him away from all whom you do not personally know\emdash "}{\f1\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 
\par }{\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 Wanda took a deep breath. Where her grandfather was concerned, anything could happen\emdash 
but Demerzel had been a First Minister over forty years ago! And he did not look much older than forty or fifty now... "This is a very peculiar request. Nobody has ever been able to convince my grandfather\emdash 
" Wanda stopped, and her eyes widened at the implications. "You think someone other than Linge Chen wants him dead?"}{\f1\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 
\par }{\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 "Linge Chen does not want Hari dead. Quite the contrary. I happen to know he rather likes your grandfather. That will not stop him from convicting and imprisoning or even executing him if
 it gives him political advantage, but my judgment is, Hari will live and be released. "}{\f1\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 
\par }{\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 "Grandfather seems convinced of that. "}{\f1\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 
\par }{\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 "Yes, well, perhaps less so now that he is in prison. "}{\f1\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 
\par }{\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 "You have been to see him?"}{\f1\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 
\par }{\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 "No, " Demerzel said. "That is not practical. "}{\f1\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 
\par }{\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 "Who would hurt my grandfather?"}{\f1\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 
\par }{\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 "I doubt he will be harmed, physically. You know of a}{\f1\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 
\par }{\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 class of mentalics stronger by far than we are?"}{\f1\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 
\par }{\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 Wanda swallowed hard, trying to find some reason not to speak to this man. He was not applying persuasion to her. H
e was not asking for confidences or for details about the others, about Star's End and the Second Foundation. "I know of one, perhaps two, " she said.}{\f1\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 
\par }{\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 "You know of Vara Liso, who now works with a man named Farad Sinter. They make a powerful team, and
 they have given you much trouble. But they are not looking for your kind now. They have shifted their search. Linge Chen is working to discredit Sinter by allowing him just enough rope, as the old saying goes, to hang himself. But Sinter has other enemie
s, and will not be allowed to go very far before he is brought up short. I suspect they will both be executed soon and will present no threat to your grandfather, or to you. "}{\f1\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 
\par }{\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 Wanda read in this statement the possibility that Liso might prove a threat to Demerzel. "To you?" she asked.}{\f1\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 
\par }{\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 "Not likely. I must go now. But I ask you to form a cordon around Hari when he is released. Hari's work is fascinating and very important. It must not be stopped!"}{\f1\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 
\par }{\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 Demerzel bowed in the old formal way, from the hips, and turned to leave.}{\f1\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 
\par }{\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 "We'd like to keep in touch with you, " Wanda called after him. "You seem to know a lot of useful things, keep your hand in\emdash "}{\f1\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 
\par }{\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 Demerzel shook his head, sadly. "You are delightful children, and your work is very important, " he said. "But I am far too much a liability to be a close friend. You are better off on your own. "}{
\f1\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 
\par }{\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 He opened the door that had been triple-locked, stepped through, nodded with gentle dignity, and closed it behind him.}{\f1\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 
\par }{\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 Stettin let out a whoosh of breath. His hair was spiky from his crude sponge bath. "Sometimes I wonder if I should have ever married you, " he said. "Your family knows the strangest people!"}{
\f1\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 
\par }{\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 Wanda stared at the door with a perplexed expression. "I couldn't read anything about him. Could you?"}{\f1\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 
\par }{\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 "No, " Stettin admitted.}{\f1\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 
\par }{\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 "He's a very practiced blank. " She shivered. "There is something very, very odd going on behind all this. Have you ever had the feeling Grandfather isn't telling us all he knows?"}{
\f1\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 
\par }{\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 "Always, " Stettin said. "But in my case, it may be because he's afraid he'll bore me. "}{\f1\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 
\par }{\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 Wanda put on her determined look. "Don't make yourself comfortable. "}{\f1\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 
\par }{\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 "Why not?" Stettin asked, then raised his hands defensively. "Not again\emdash "}{\f1\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 
\par }{\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 "We're moving. Everyone is moving again. "}{\f1\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 
\par }{\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 "Sky!" Stettin swore, and flung the towel into a corner. "He said he thought Hari's going to win!"}{\f1\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 
\par }{\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 "What does he know?" Wanda said grimly.}{\f1\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 
\par }{\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 The narrative, the testimony, all the events of the Trial come down to us through suspect sources. The best source, of course, is Gaal Dornick; but
 as has been mentioned many times already, Dornick had been subject to editing and pruning over the centuries. He seems to have been a faithful observer, but current scholarship suggests that even the length of the Trial, the continuity of trial days, may
 be suspect...}{\f1\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 
\par }{\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 \emdash Encyclopedia Galactica, 117th edition, 1054 RE.}{\f1\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 
\par }{\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 48.}{\f1\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 
\par }{\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 Hari slept fitfully at irregular intervals. His room was always kept fully lighted, and, of course, he was allowed no artificial sleep aids or eyeshades. He had decided this was Chen's way 
of softening him up before his testimony in the trial.}{\f1\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 
\par }{\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 He would not see Sedjar Boon for at least another day, and he doubted Boon would be able to get Chen to turn out the lights at civilized intervals. Hari coped as best he could. Actually, since an old m
an slept fitfully and irregularly anyway, the hardship was more to his sense of justice and dignity than to his mental health.}{\f1\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 
\par }{\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 Still, there were odd moments for him when he seemed to slide between waking and dreaming. He would jerk to full consciousness, s
taring at a blank pastel pink wall, having seen something significant, even wonderful, but not remembering what it was. Memory? Dream? Revelation? AH could hold equal weight in this damned unchanging cell. How much worse would it have been in the previous
 cell?}{\f1\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 
\par }{\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 
Hari took to pacing, the famed exercise of the imprisoned man. He had precisely six meters to pace in one direction, three another. A veritable luxury compared to the other cell . . . But not enough to give him any feeling of accom-}{
\f1\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 
\par }{\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 plishment. After a few hours, he stopped that as well.}{\f1\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 
\par }{\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 
He had been in this cell less than four days, and already he was regretting his past love of small, enclosed spaces. He had been born beneath the wide skies of Helicon, and had at first found these covered environs a l
ittle daunting, even depressing, but his long decades on Trantor had gradually inured him. Then he had come to prefer them... Until now.}{\f1\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 
\par }{\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 He could not understand why he had ever adopted the use of the Trantorian expletive of "Sky!"}{\f1\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 
\par }{\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 Again, an hour passed wit
hout his notice. He got up from the small desk and rubbed his hands together; they tingled slightly. What if he became ill and died before going to trial? All the preparations, all Hari's machinations, all the tugged and woven threads of political influen
ce\emdash for nothing!}{\f1\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 
\par }{\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 
He began to sweat. Perhaps his mind was going. Chen would not shy from using drugs to debilitate him, would he? The Chief Commissioner used his dedication to Imperial justice as a convenient mask, surely; but Hari still could not bring himse
lf to believe that Chen was exceptionally intelligent. Blunt measures might suit Chen perfectly, and he had enough power to conceal the evidence, destroy it.}{\f1\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 
\par }{\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 Destroy Hari Seldon, without his even knowing. "I hate power. I hate the powerful. " Yet Hari had 
himself once held power, even quietly reveled in it, certainly not shied away from wielding it. Hari had ordered the suppression of the Chaos Worlds\emdash those brief and tragic flowerings of excess creativity and dissent. Why?}{
\f1\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 
\par }{\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 He had imprisoned them in politica
l and financial strait-jackets. He regretted that necessity most of all the things he had done in the name of psychohistory... And this legacy had been left untouched for the heavy hand of Linge Chen and Klayus to swing like a bludgeon.}{
\f1\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 
\par }{\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 He lay back on the cot and stared at the ceiling. Was it}{\f1\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 
\par }{\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 night, above the metal skin of Trantor? Night beneath the domes, with the darkling sunset and midnight ceils of the municipalities announcing an end to the day's labors?}{\f1\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 

\par }{\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 For him, for Hari, what labors?}{\f1\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 
\par }{\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 
He dreamed he was a pan again, in the garden park, with Dors playing an opposite female, their minds welded to the minds of the simians. The threat to his life, and Dors' defense. Power and play and danger and victory in such close combinations. Heady.}{
\f1\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 
\par }{\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 Now, this punishment.}{\f1\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 
\par }{\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 
Claustrophilia. That was what Yugo had called the love of the metal-skinned worlds' inhabitants for their confinement. Yet there had always been worlds buried in rock, always been worlds clad at least in part in metal shields against 
the wet and violent skies. Sky. The curse. Sky. The freedom.}{\f1\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 
\par }{\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 "Our Father in Heaven forgives you as He forgives all the transgressions of the saints. "}{\f1\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 
\par }{\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 This lovely female voice floated through his vague thoughts. He knew it instantly. There was something at once rich and ancient about it, a voice from a time before most human memory.}{
\f1\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 
\par }{\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 Joan! What a strange dream this is. You're gone, decades gone. You helped me when I was First Minister\emdash but I gave you your freedom to travel with the wraiths, the meme-minds, to
 the stars. You are an almost forgotten bit of history for me now. How seldom I think of you!}{\f1\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 
\par }{\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 "How often I think of you. Saint Hari, who has sacrificed his life for\emdash "}{\f1\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 
\par }{\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 I'm no saint! I've suppressed the dreams of billions.}{\f1\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 
\par }{\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 "How well I know. Our debate many d
ecades ago collapsed much as the bright candles of a thousand dissenting and restless Renaissance worlds have been snuffed... For the sake of divine order, the grand scheme. We helped you in your first position of power, in exchange for our freedom, and}{
\f1\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 
\par }{\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 the freedom of all the meme-minds. But Voltaire and I quarreled again\emdash 
it was inevitable. I was beginning to see a larger picture, encompassing your work as part of the divine plan. Voltaire flew away in disgust, across the Galaxy, leaving me here, to contemp
late all I had learned. Now comes your time of Trial, and I fear you risk a darker despair than the time at Gethsemane for our Lord. "}{\f1\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 
\par }{\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 At this, Hari had to laugh and half cry at once. Voltaire despised me at the last. Snuffing out freedom, suppressing the 
Renaissance Worlds. And you didn't think that way about me when last we talked. He seemed to be half awake, and wholly enmeshed in this... vision! / made love to a machine for years. By your conception, your philosophy\emdash }{
\f1\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 
\par }{\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 "I have acquired more wisdom, more understanding. You were given an angel, a partner-protector. She was sent by the emissaries of God, and ordained for her task by the supreme emissary. "}{
\f1\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 
\par }{\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 Hari was too frightened now, an almost panic darkness in his mind, to ask who that might be, in this imaginary Joan's conception. But\emdash Who? Who is that?}{\f1\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 
\par }{\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 "The Eternal, who opposes the forces of chaos. Daneel, who was Demerzel. "}{\f1\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 
\par }{\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 Now he knew this was out of his own mind, worse than a dream. Once you acquiesced in the killing of the machines\emdash the robots.}{\f1\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 
\par }{\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 "I have seen deeper truths. "}{\f1\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 
\par }{\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 Hari felt the tight strictures of Daneel's controls. Please go, leave me be! he said, and rolled over on the cot.}{\f1\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 
\par }{\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 As he rolled, his eyes swung open and he saw an old, broken-down tiktok standing near him in his cell. He shoved up from the cot.}{\f1\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 
\par }{\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 The cell's door was still closed and locked.}{\f1\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 
\par }{\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 The tiktok was marked with prison colors, yellow and black. It must have been a maintenance machine before the tik-toks rebelled, threatened the Empire, and were deactivated. He}{
\f1\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 
\par }{\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 could not imagine how it would have gotten into the cell, unless it had been sent on purpose.}{\f1\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 
\par }{\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 The tiktok backed away with a sandy whine, and a face appeared in front of the ma
chine, about a meter and a half above the floor, a projection, followed by a body, small and slender and strong, as if brushed in, wrapping around the tiktok like a shadow in a bright room.}{\f1\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 
\par }{\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 Hari's neck hair rose with sharp prickles, and his breath seemed to stick in his chest. For a moment, as if caught in a nightmare, he could not speak. Then he sucked in a breath and jerked away from the machine.}{
\f1\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 
\par }{\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 "Help!" he screamed, his voice cracking. Panic darkness seemed to fill him. His chest might have been collapsing. All the fear, all the tension, the anticipation\emdash }{\f1\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 

\par }{\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 "Do not cry out, Hari!" The voice was vaguely female, mechanical in the old tiktok way.}{\f1\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 
\par }{\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 "I mean no harm, no concern. "}{\f1\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 
\par }{\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 "Joan!" He breathed this name aloud, but much more softly.}{\f1\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 
\par }{\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 But the old machine was failing, its last power draining. Hari sat up on the side of the bed and watched the lights on its body slowly dim.}{\f1\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 
\par }{\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 "Take courage, Hari Seldon. He and I stand in opposition now, once more, as we always did. We have quarrelllleed. " The words slurred, slowed. "We haaawe seppparrrrateddd. "}{\f1\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 

\par }{\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 The tiktok stopped dead.}{\f1\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 
\par }{\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 The hatch burst open with a loud sigh and three guards entered. One immediately fired a bolt weapon that blew the old tiktok down to the floor. The others booted and kicked 
the small unit into a corner and shielded Hari from anything more it might do. Two more guards entered and dragged Hari out of the cell by his shoulders. Feebly, Hari kicked his heels against the smooth floor to help the men along.}{
\f1\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 
\par }{\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 "Are you sure you don't want me dead?" he asked querulously.}{\f1\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 
\par }{\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 "Sky, no!" the guard on his right cried out brusquely. "It would mean our lives if you're hurt. You're in the most secure cell on Trantor\emdash "}{\f1\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 
\par }{\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 "So we thought, " the other guard said grimly, and they lifted Hari to his feet
 and tried to brush him down. They had dragged him ten or fifteen meters down the straight corridor. Hari stared at this immense, welcome distance, this refreshing extension, and caught his breath.}{\f1\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 
\par }{\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 "Maybe you should treat an old cuss like me more gently, "
 he suggested, and started to laugh raucously, a cackle, a hoot, a suck of breath, then more laughter. The laughter stopped abruptly and he shouted, "Keep the ghosts out of my monk's quarters, damn you!"}{\f1\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 
\par }{\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 The guards stared at him, then at each other.}{\f1\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 
\par }{\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 It was hours before they took him back into his cell. The intrusion was never explained.}{\f1\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 
\par }{\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 Joan and Voltaire, the resurrected "sims" or simulated intelligences, modeled after lost historical figures, had given him so much trouble and so much information\emdash decades pa
st, when he had been at the height of his mature youth, First Minister of the Empire, and Dors had constantly been at his side.}{\f1\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 
\par }{\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 Hari had forgotten about them, but now Joan, at least, was back, riding a mechanical contrivance into his prison cell, subvertin
g all the security systems. She had decided against leaving with the meme-minds, to explore the Galaxy...}{\f1\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 
\par }{\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 And what about Voltaire? What more trouble could either or both of them cause, with their ancient brilliance and their ability to infiltrate and repro
gram the machines and communications and computational systems of Trantor?}{\f1\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 
\par }{\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 They were certainly beyond his control. And if Joan favored Hari, whom would Voltaire favor? They had certainly}{\f1\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 
\par }{\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 represented opposite points of view through most of their career...}{\f1\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 
\par }{\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 But at least someone from the past was still around, professed concern for him! He did not have Dors, or Raych, or Yugo... or Daneel...}{\f1\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 
\par }{\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 Perversely, the more he thought about the visitation, the less disturbed he became. Hours passed, and he slipped into a d
eep and restful slumber, as if he had been touched by something profoundly convinced and at peace.}{\f1\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 
\par }{\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 49.}{\f1\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 
\par }{\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 Lodovik held the head of R. Giskard Reventlov and stood motionless for several minutes, lost in deep processing of what he had absorbed\emdash lost in contemplation. He set the head down gently on the plinth.}{
\f1\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 
\par }{\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 Kallusin kept a respectful silence.}{\f1\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 
\par }{\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 Lodovik turned toward the humaniform Calvinian. "They were very difficult times," he said. "Humans seemed intent on destroying each other. The Solarians and Aurorans\emdash the Spacers\emdash 
were very difficult cultures."}{\f1\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 
\par }{\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 "All humans present grave difficulties," Kallusin said. "Serving them is never easy."}{\f1\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 
\par }{\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 "No," Lodovik agreed. "But to take on the responsibility of destroying an entire world\emdash the home world of humanity, as Giskard did ..
. To push human history onto a proximate beneficial course . . . That is extraordinary."}{\f1\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 
\par }{\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 "Few robots not perverted by human prejudices and inappropriate programming would have done such a thing."}{\f1\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 
\par }{\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 "You believe Giskard was operating improperly?"}{\f1\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 
\par }{\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 "Is it not obvious?" Kallusin asked.}{\f1\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 
\par }{\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 "But a robot that is malfunctioning so severely in its basic instructions must shut down, become totally inactive."}{\f1\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 
\par }{\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 "You have not shut down," Kallusin noted dryly.}{\f1\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 
\par }{\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 "I have had such constraints removed\emdash Giskard had not. Besides, I haven't committed such crimes!"}{\f1\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 
\par }{\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 "Indeed. And so Giskard ceased functioning. "}{\f1\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 
\par }{\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 "But not before setting in motion all these events, these trends!"}{\f1\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 
\par }{\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 Kallusin nodded. "Clearly, we have more latitude than our designers ever planned for. "}{\f1\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 
\par }{\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 "The humans thought they were rid of us. But they could not sweep all the worlds where robots still existed\emdash and where Giskard's virus grew. Nor, apparently, did all humans agree to dispose of their robots. "}{
\f1\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 
\par }{\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 "There were other factors, other events, " Kallusin said. "Plussix remembers little but that robots knew sin. "}{\f1\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 
\par }{\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 Lodovik turned to Kallusin, breaking his contemplation of the silvery head, and felt again the out-of-place and untraceable resonance. "By seeking to constrain human freedom, " he suggested.}{
\f1\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 
\par }{\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 "No, " Kallusin said. "That was what led to the schism between Giskardians and Calvinians. Those who broke away from Daneel's faction carried out instructions given cent
uries before by humans on Aurora. What those instructions were\emdash "}{\f1\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 
\par }{\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 The word or name attached to the resonance suddenly became clear. Not Voldarr, but Voltaire. A human personality, with humanlike memories. This is what the meme-minds hated. I have swum throu
gh space with them, across light-years, through the last remnants ofwormholes abandoned by humanity... This is why they took revenge on your kind on Trantor!}{\f1\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 
\par }{\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 Images, comparisons rose unbidden. "A vast burning, winnowing, an extirpation, " Lodovik said, shu
ddering at the human emotion of anger, not his own. Shuddering also at the return of his malfunction, never leaving him alone long enough to enjoy stability. "Serving humanity but not justice. A prairie fire. "}{\f1\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 

\par }{\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 Kallusin regarded him with curiosity. "You know of these events? Plussix has never revealed them to me. "}{\f1\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 
\par }{\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 Lodovik shook his head. "I am puzzled by what I just said. I do not know where the words come from. "}{\f1\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 
\par }{\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 "Perhaps exposure to these histories, these memories\emdash "}{\f1\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 
\par }{\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 "Perhaps. They disturb and inform. We should return to Plussix. I am far more curious now what his plans are, and how we shall proceed. "}{\f1\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 
\par }{\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 They left the chamber where Giskard's head was stored and climbed the spiral stairs to the upper warehouse level.}{\f1\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 
\par }{\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 50.}{\f1\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 
\par }{\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 Mors Planch was summoned from his well-appointed cell, not far from the private office of Farad Sinter. The guard who came to fetch him was of pure citizen stock, strong and unquestioning and taciturn.}{
\f1\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 
\par }{\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 "How is Farad Sinter today?" Planch asked.}{\f1\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 
\par }{\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 No answer.}{\f1\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 
\par }{\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 "And you? You feel well?" Planch lifted an inquiring and sympathetic eyebrow.}{\f1\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 
\par }{\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 A nod.}{\f1\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 
\par }{\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 "I am feeling a little uneasy myself. You see, this Sinter is every bit as terrible a human being as\emdash "}{\f1\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 
\par }{\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 A warning frown.}{\f1\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 
\par }{\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 "Yes, but unlike you, I want to incur his wrath. He will kill me sooner or later, or what he has done will lead to my death\emdash 
 I don't doubt that at all. He smells of death and corruption. He represents the worst the Empire can summon these days\emdash "}{\f1\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 
\par }{\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 The guard shook his head in remonstration and stepped around to open the door to the new Chief Commissioner of the Commission of General Security. Mors Planch closed his eyes, sucked in a deep breath, and entered.}{
\f1\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 
\par }{\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 "Welcome," Sinter said. He stood in his new robes,}{\f1\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 
\par }{\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 even more grand (and much gaudier) tha
n those of Linge Chen. His tailor, a small Lavrentian with a worried face, probably new to the palace, stood back and folded his hands as this new master enjoyed the unfinished work, and delayed its completion. "Mors Planch, I'm sure you will be delighted
 to know we have captured a robot. Vara Liso actually found it, and it did not escape. "}{\f1\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 
\par }{\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 The small, intense, and thoroughly discomfiting woman had almost managed to hide behind Sinter, but now she bowed and acknowledged this praise. She did not look happy, however.}{
\f1\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 
\par }{\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 Sky, she's ugly, Planch thought, and at the same time felt pity for her. Then she looked directly at him, narrowed one eye, and the pity froze in his veins.}{\f1\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 
\par }{\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 "There may be robots everywhere, as I suspected, theorized, and as you discovered, Mors. " Sinter submitted to the tailor once more, lowering his arms and holding still. "Tell our witness about your find, Vara. "}{
\f1\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 
\par }{\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 "It was an old robot, " Liso said breathlessly. "A humani-form, in terrible condition, haunting the dark places of the municipalities, a pitiful thing\emdash "}{\f1\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 
\par }{\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 "But a robot, " Sinter said, "the first found in any kind of working order in thousands of years. Imagine! Surviving like a rodent all these centuries. "}{\f1\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 
\par }{\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 "Its mind is weak, " Liso commented softly. "Its energy reserves are very low. It will not last much longer. "}{\f1\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 
\par }{\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 "We shall take it before the Emperor this evening, then, tomorrow, I shall demand that my interview with Hari Sel-don be moved forward. My sources tell me Chen is ready to give in and strike a deal with Seldon
\emdash the coward! The trai-torl This evidence, along with your tape, should convince the worst skeptic. Linge Chen had hoped to destroy me. Soon I shall have more power than all the Commission of Public Safety's stuffy barons combined\emdash 
and just in time to save us all from servitude to these machines. "}{\f1\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 
\par }{\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 Planch stood with hands folded before him, head lowered, and said nothing.}{\f1\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 
\par }{\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 Sinter glared at him. "You're not happy at this news? You should be delighted. It means you'll have an official pardon for your transgressions. You have proved invaluable. "}{\f1\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 

\par }{\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 "But we have not found Lodovik Trema, " Liso whispered, barely audible.}{\f1\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 
\par }{\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 "Give us time!" Sinter crowed. "We'll find all of them. Now\emdash let's bring in the machine!"}{\f1\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 
\par }{\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 "You should not drain its energies, " Liso said, almost as if she felt pity for it.}{\f1\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 
\par }{\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 "It's lasted thousands of years, " Sinter said lightly, unperturbed. "It will last a few weeks more, and that's all I need. "}{\f1\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 
\par }{\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 Planch stiffened and stood to one side as the broad door opened again. Another guard entered, followed by four more, surroun
ding a shabbily dressed figure about Planch's height, slim but not thin, hair ragged and face stained with dirt. Its eyes seemed flat, listless. The guards carried high-powered stun weapons, easily capable of shorting out the robot and frying its internal
 works.}{\f1\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 
\par }{\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 "A female, " Sinter said, "as you see. How interesting\emdash  female robots! And fully capable sexually, I understand\emdash 
 examined by one of our physicians. Makes me wonder if in the past humans actually made robots to bear children! What would the children be like, us\emdash 
or them? Biological, or mechanical? Not this one, however. Nothing besides the cosmetic and pneumatic\emdash not fully practical. "}{\f1\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 
\par }{\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 The feminine robot stood alone and silent as the guards withdrew, weapons held ready.}{\f1\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 
\par }{\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 "If only the recent attempt on the Emperor's life had been made by a robot, " Sinter said, then added unctuously, "Sky forbid!"}{\f1\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 
\par }{\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 Planch narrowed his eyes. The man's political savvy was weakening with every moment of perceived glory.}{\f1\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 
\par }{\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 Vara Liso approached the robot with a worried expres-}{\f1\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 
\par }{\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 sio
n. "This one is so like a human, " she muttered. "Even now it's difficult to pick her out from, say, you, or you, Farad. " She pointed at Planch and then at Sinter. "She has humanlike thoughts, even humanlike concerns. I felt something similar in the robo
t we could not capture\emdash "}{\f1\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 
\par }{\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 "The one that got away. " Sinter smiled broadly.}{\f1\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 
\par }{\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 "Yes. He seemed almost human\emdash maybe even more human than this one. "}{\f1\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 
\par }{\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 "Well, let us not forget they are none of them human, " Sinter said. "What you feel is the creative drollery of engineers thousands of years dead. "}{\f1\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 
\par }{\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 "The one we could not capture... " She looked directly at Mors Planch and once again he suppressed a shiver. "He was bulkier, not very good-looking, with a distinct character to
 his face. I would have thought he was human... but for this flavor to his thoughts. He was about the same size and shape as the shorter, bulkier robot on your tape. "}{\f1\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 
\par }{\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 "See? We almost had him, " Sinter said. "Just that close. " He pinched his fingers toget
her. "And we'll have him yet. Lodovik Trema and all the others. Even the tall one whose name we do not know... " Sinter approached the feminine robot. It wobbled slightly on its mechanical ankles, but there came no mechanical sound from its frame.}{
\f1\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 
\par }{\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 "Do you 
know the name of the one I am looking for?" Sinter asked. The robot turned to face him. Its voice emerged from parted jaws and writhing lips, a harsh croak. It spoke an old dialect of Galactic Standard, not heard on Trantor for thousands of years, except 
by scholars, just barely understandable.}{\f1\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 
